text: I don't usually like huge merchandising. Movies meant only to be watched by big audiences and to earn money. But I honestly believe The Hunger Games is not one of those. Yes, it is famous, and yes, it is huge. But there is a real story, a real plot behind it. It's not a book necessarily meant for teenagers, only because the main character is a teenager; it doesn't talk about youth and naiveness and love and guys. And if you read "Mockingjay", you would certainly know that it's about¬†war, and its consequences, and life, and how to deal with our losses, and what death leaves behind in those who keep living, and social engineering, and manipulation, and power, and politics. And these are deep themes that a very smart author, Collins, has been able to explain to young generations through a book that's really simple to read. And the world she describes is certainly not something so far from the one we're living in. She (and the creators of the movie) are just giving us something to think about.Ôªø So I do not see the point in criticising a movie like this.Ôªø

text: SPOILER ALERT:    I understand why people think that Mockingjay should be just one movie, however, even though it's one book, it's kind of comprised of two parts.  1. Katniss and her family seeking refuge in District 13, which actually survived the war, and was spared by the Capitol and kept secret because of the fact they owned WMDs.This first part also has Peeta (who went insane) and Finnick's disabled wife (whose name I forget) being captured by the Capitol and put on live TV, only for Peeta to reveal the Capitol's plans to bomb District 13.  2. The second part consists of Katniss and a team of rebels invading District 1 because it provides a defense for the Capitol. The rebels then attack the Capitol. However, whilst they are there, a large group of young children are bombed, as ordered by President Grey, leader of District 13. Once the rebels capture President Snow, Katniss is chosen to execute him, but she choses to kill Grey instead. President Snow then chokes on his own blood. In the end Katniss and Peeta are married and have kids. Ah, yes, and Prim dies.   While these events could fit in one film, I think it is best they are separated into these two parts, because of the way the first builds up to the second, and because of the way the second is a very obvious conclusion.

text: I hope they use creative licence for both Part One and Part Two, because I actually see a lot of Oscar potential in these final two films. Yes, I know Mockingjay (the book) was a disappointment and lazily written, but there was a lot of points that the author merely touched on or hadn't thought of that were in the book, and the evolution of Katniss is haunting; the plot was also the most complex and mature of the three books. I feel like the darkness and drama, the brutality and devastation of war and the cruelty of the brainwashing Capitol, as well as the psychologically complex themes explored within the book, could be seriously expanded and developed upon in these films, showing stuff that could be happening at the same time that wasn't shown in the book, without veering away from the chronological events.
